observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
a. Require the preparation of and submission not only of the LBAc Form Nos. 5 and 6 but all other required local budgeting forms, which are vital in monitoring the accomplishments, performance, and efficiency of the Municipality in delivering good governance and public service;
b. Direct the concerned end users, Municipal Budget Officer, and Municipal Accountant to obligate expenditures as they are incurred;
c. Direct the Municipal Accountant to exercise prudence and scrutiny in transferring funds from one fund to another and facilitate only those that are necessary and compliant with laws, rules, and regulations; and
d. Instruct the concerned offices, spearheaded by the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator, and the Local Finance Committee, to conduct regular review and general examination of cost and accomplishments against performance standards applied in undertaking the much-needed programs/projects/ activities.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct:
a. The concerned implementing offices to expedite the implementation of the PPAs to utilize the fund transfers within the prescribed period, and observe strictly the parameters set in the Memorandum of Agreement; 
b. The Municipal Accountant to exhaust efforts in retrieving the supporting documents and expediting the return of the retrieval of unexpended balances to documents; 
c. The Municipal Accountant to maintain a separate subsidiary ledger for each funded project/program/activity and ensure prompt recording of the subsequent liquidation reports; 
d. The Municipal Accountant to send confirmation letters to the Source Agencies to validate the balance per books of the prior years’ unutilized fund transfers; and 
e. The Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with the concerned implementing offices upon receipt of fund transfers from various NGAs for the timely implementation by the said offices.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the concerned departments/offices to:

Plan effectively the priority development projects to be included in the AIP by considering their feasibility and necessity;

Analyze and reconcile the discrepancies in the amounts reflected in the SAAOB and the QRGPPA in totality and not only for those pertaining to the 20% DF.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:
a. Local Finance Committee to adopt strategy in order to increase revenue/collections and monitor properly the availability of cash every month to ensure that all disbursements have cash back up;
b. Municipal Treasurer to prepare Daily Cash Position Report to serve as guide to him in certifying that funds are available to ensure that all disbursements have cash back up;
c. Municipal Budget Officer, Municipal Accountant, and Municipal Treasurer to exercise diligence, prudence and proper control in the disposition of the Municipality’s funds and limit expenditures within the total income realized and collected during the year to avoid incurrence of cash overdraft;
d. the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to explain why the Trust Fund was utilized and disbursed other than its intended purpose contrary to Section 309 (b) of RA 7160 and Section 84 of PD 1445, thus, resulted in the incurrence of cash overdraft amounting to ₱30,856,963.83 in the Trust Fund. Likewise, we recommended to the Municipal Mayor to instruct the Local Finance Committee to closely monitor the utilization of funds, consider different strategies to increase the Municipality’s income and intensify collection, impose additional cost-cutting measures, prioritize projects and programs, and limit the incurrence of obligations to the extent of cash availability.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor and the concerned LGU Officials submit the following relevant documents in order to facilitate thorough evaluation of the propriety of the disbursement of funds in the implementation of this project:
a. Justification on the delays incurred in the submission of the required documents for the release of loan with DBP;
b. Lacking documents necessary in the billing payments;
c. The amended contract for the revised estimates and change of name of the winning bidders of the Joint Venture; 
d. Letter from DBP showing the items deleted in the Items of Work;
e. Variation orders, if any, for the additions in the Items of Work and the sources of fund.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor enjoin the:
a. adopt and enforce appropriate issuances to institutionalize the re-organization of GAD Focal Point System in accordance with PCW-DILG-DBM and NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01 and ensure that all members including elected local officials and department heads undergo capability building programs on GAD;
b. require the MPDC to spearhead the setting up and maintenance of the GAD database;
c. create the LGU GFPS or its TWG who will provide technical assistance to the MPDC; submit GAD Plan and Budget to the Provincial Planning and Development Office to ensure GAD PPAs alignment and have it reviewed and approved by the DILG Regional Office; ensure mainstreaming of GAD concerns in the local development plans; lead the preparation of the annual LGU GAD Accomplishment Report and other GAD reports; and
d. the Municipal Budget Officer to include in their yearly budget the statutory requirement of at least five percent (5%) of the total appropriations for GAD; ensure the utilization of 5% GAD Budget only on PPAs which address gender issues and concerns.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct:
a) the Municipal Accountant to religiously demand for the prompt liquidation of their cash advances following the prescribed period and ensure that all claims are completely supported;
b) the concerned personnel to refund the total claims of ₱4,277.00 which are not allowed in audit;
c) the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to refrain from granting cash advance to employees who are not designated as disbursing officers for purposes other than travel;
d) the concerned officials to submit explanation on the noted inconsistencies on the dates of the supporting official receipts;
e) the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to stop the practice of granting cash advances to elected officials when it is not to be used for traveling expenses as prescribed in Section 4.1.4 of COA Circular 97-002.
